<br>
  That is *TOO* funny.<br>
<br>
AnyariLorien,<br>
<br>
  I don't think Sony does this, but if the actual notes.txt commands (when you type /note something) are sent to the server (I don't think they are, but am not sure) - yes.<br>
<br>
  What's more, all they would have to do is change something in the client that did just that.  Regarding the EULA:<br>
<br>
&quot;9. You may not use any third party software to modify the Software to change Game play. You may not use our intellectual property rights contained in the Game or the Software to create or provide any other means through which the Game may be played by others, as through server emulators. <!--EZCODE BOLD START--><b> You may not take any action which imposes an unreasonable or disproportionately large load on our infrastructure.</b><!--EZCODE BOLD END--> You may not sell or auction any EverQuest characters, items, coin or copyrighted material.&quot;<br>
<br>
  The use of the /note command, and if it fell in the above bolded category is open to debate.  It seems it would leave a loop-hole for them to pretty much do whatever they wanted at their discretion.<br>
<br>
  The point there is that you wouldn't even have to be told in the EULA anything different than you are now for them to &quot;flip that switch&quot;.  And what's more, they might already have that switch to flip but just dont do it for everyone.  Although, I doubt this is the case since these types of tools are so low-key -- who knows.<br>
<br>
  So, back to your question, can you run it on a second computer?  <!--EZCODE BOLD START--><b> Yes</b><!--EZCODE BOLD END-->.  Can they detect it. <!--EZCODE BOLD START--><b> Yes.</b><!--EZCODE BOLD END-->  Are they detecting it?  <!--EZCODE BOLD START--><b> Doubtfully, probably on a per suspect basis, if at all. </b><!--EZCODE BOLD END--><br>
